{{Infobox language |name=Ngoya |altname=Kibala |nativename=''Ipala'' |states=[[Angola]] |region= northeast [[Cuanza Sul Province]] |ethnicity= |speakers=100,000 |date=2013 |ref=<ref name=RELV>Angenot et al. (2013) [http://www.periodicos.unir.br/index.php/linguaviva/article/download/727/776 "Comparison between the Ipala-Ngoya, Kimbundu and Umbundu tone-class systems"], ''Revista Língua Viva'' vol. 3, no. 1.</ref> |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo languages|Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Benue–Congo languages|Benue–Congo]] |fam4=[[Southern Bantoid languages|Southern Bantoid]] |fam5=[[Bantu languages|Bantu]] |fam6=(transitional between zones [[Guthrie classification of Bantu languages#Zone H|Zone H]] and [[Guthrie classification of Bantu languages#Zone R|Zone R]]) |minority=Angola |iso3=none |glotto=none |glottorefname= |guthrie=none }}
'''Ngoya''', also known as '''Pala''' (Kibala, Ipala), is a newly recognized language of [[Angola]] that since ca. 2010 has been used for national radio broadcasts. It had previously been considered a dialect of [[Kimbundu]] without any linguistic evidence, and appears to be transitional between Kimbundu and [[Umbundu]].
Nyoya is spoken in [[Cuanza Sul]] between [[Songo language|Songo]] to the north and Umbundu to the south.
The name "Ngoya" is an Umbundu word meaning "savage". The endonym is ''Pala'', which with the noun-class-7 prefix is ''Íipàlà''. It is frequently rendered as ''Kibala'', which is the Kimbundu form.<ref name=RELV/>
