==Language==
The Sihanaka speak a dialect of the [[Malagasy language]], which is a branch of the [[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian language group]] derived from the [[Barito languages]], spoken in southern [[Borneo]].{{sfn|Adelaar|Himmelmann|2005|page=456}}

==Economy==
By the mid-1600s, the Sihanaka had already established themselves as one of the island's most important trading groups. Their location on the main trade route between the coast and the [[Merina people|Merina]] capital of [[Antananarivo]] enabled them to become important trading partners beginning in the 18th century; slave trading was a major source of income until outlawed under [[Radama I]] in the 1810s.{{sfn|Ogot|1992|page=431}} The Sihanaka women also produced pottery, which was baked using wood collected by men in the surrounding forests.{{sfn|Gennep|1904|page=155}}

Since the end of slave trading, the Sihanaka largely derived their livelihoods from rice farming. Their region is among the most productive on the island.{{sfn|Thompson|Adloff|1965|page=264}} Wealth is unequally distributed, with the wealthy owning the majority of the fertile land, which is either rented to the poor or worked by them for low wages.{{sfn|Cipollone|2008|page=103}}

Members of this community also herd zebu and catch fish in Lake Alaotra.{{sfn|Thompson|Adloff|1965|page=264}} The work of fishing was traditionally subdivided by gender: men were only allowed to fish for eels, while women were tasked to use nets to catch small fish, and children were the only ones allowed to fish using poles. Men and children would traditionally leave their catch on the shore for women to pick up and take back to the village.{{sfn|Gennep|1904|page=155}}

The Sihanaka are one of the few Malagasy groups who historically branded their cattle.{{sfn|Gennep|1904|page=188}} This was done by clipping the ear of the cow and was a religious act conducted once annually on a dedicated day of feasting.{{sfn|Gennep|1904|page=193}} Cattle generally belonged to the community as a whole and were used principally to assist with farming.{{sfn|Gennep|1904|page=190}}

